## 1. Supervision and Accountability

The number one thing is I have supervision. Okay, credit where credit's due: my dad was really a big part of why, in the beginning at least, I kept it going.

Because let's face it, there are only so many fun things you can do to learn English, right? After you listen to enough English songs, after you watch enough TV shows, at some point you still got to return to your dictionary. You still got to whip out your notebook. You still got to learn the boring stuff. And that part never gets easy, especially in the beginning when you don't really know if you're making progress.

I have my dad to thank for that because he would call me up every single day to just to check in with me. At that point, it's just about how much time I've put in. And so just having him check in on me every single day or every other day was a big help.

**Create Your Own Accountability System**
If you don't have an elder to kind of check in on you and put you in your place, you can find a peer. You can find an accountability partner, an accountability system. You can do it in a group and then you can meet every single week and talk about what you've done this week.

For that purpose, I like to start a support group—a study group where five to ten people compose one single group and we go over every single person's study routine and study plan for the week. We meet at the end of the week to discuss how everyone is doing. (This is provided that you've gotten a one-on-one consultation or read my self-study guide so you know what I'm talking about and what methods would work.)

In that particular group, we're not necessarily learning anything new. We're just checking in on every single person. We're holding ourselves as well as other people accountable.

By the way, this is something I'm doing currently in my real life. I have this friend that I meet. Prior to meeting either online or in person, we have to fill out a worksheet asking questions like: *Oh, what are your main goals for the week? What are your absolute to-do, must-do lists for the week? What are your goals for the future?* All that kind of stuff. And then by the end of the week, we check in on each other to see if you fulfilled everything. And if not, what was the reason? Maybe there is something deeper.

So in this study group, in this accountability group, we do the same thing. Okay, we get deep. Maybe it's some mentality issue. Sometimes it's not necessarily people's intelligence. It's not even that they don't have the right methods, they don't have the right tools, they don't have the right guidance. Come on, we live in an age of information overload, information abundance. You can find all the information out there.

I think sometimes it's just that we don't have people expecting us. Particularly when you graduate, you don't have teachers or students or parents holding us accountable for anything "extracurricular." Let's just call it right? It's not work, it's not family, it's not your physical health. English for a lot of people is a luxury, or learning anything new is a luxury for most people, particularly when you have limited time.

Having that accountability system was really crucial for me, was really important for me, at least in the beginning. I mean, my dad didn't keep calling me for the remainder of my learning journey. But when I was little, when I was 16 or 17, it really did help 'cause I have poor self-discipline. I mean, I still do, but I know myself enough to pre-commit. I call people up. I know my "lazy tendencies," let's call it that.

## 2. Warm Up and Ease Into It

Number two is to warm up. I have my notes say: **Do something you like in that language and do it incrementally so you don't feel like you're doing a chore.**

So I still vividly remember how I even got interested in English. How I didn't feel this aversion towards English was because nobody really forced me to learn anything. And specifically, nobody forced me to do a bunch of exercises to really take it as like a study, a subject to study. I more or less just eased into this subject altogether, eased into this language altogether.

I was already listening to English songs. My parents were listening to English songs. My parents were watching American TV shows (some of them are really violent that they probably shouldn't have exposed me to before I was even taking classes in school and stuff). I was already exposed to the language. I had already developed a taste for English TV shows, English books, without all the negative association that many people have—maybe they've been chastised by their teachers or maybe they've been ridiculed by people with their pronunciation and stuff.

So I think in the beginning, whether you're learning English or learning anything new, just dabble a little bit. Just have fun with it. Don't immediately dive into a study routine. Watch certain TV shows, but maybe watch the subtitles too. Pay attention to the English subtitles too. Listen to a few English songs, mimic their sounds, and let your interest, let your curiosity take over. That way, in the long run, you won't be annoyed, you won't be irritated by this process because it *does* get tedious at times. It doesn't get hard, it just gets boring and repetitive and monotonous.

